<div id="comment_status_64680530" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64680530" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64680530" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a rel="nofollow" id="comment_link_64680530" name="comment_link_64680530" href="//yro.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23409794&amp;cid=64680530" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64680530)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64680530" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64680530); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~erice">erice</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~erice">( 13380 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64680530"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64680530"><p><div class="quote"><p>...but I dare say in all software.</p></div><p>Certainly.  By framing the challenge in terms of open source software, the competitors don't need to be vetted for special access and you get solutions that can be thoroughly checked by many eyes.   That's a good project.</p><p>However, once a solution is found (if a good solution is found), the same process can be applied to closed source and even secret code.  There are never enough eyes looking at secret code.  DARPA's first priority is "defence" so securing secret code is most dear to them.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64680530">

</div>
</div>

