<ul id="group_64680530">
	<li id="hiddens_64680530" class="hide"></li>
</ul>

</li></ul></li><li id="tree_64679470" class="comment oneline"><span class="ind"></span>
<div id="comment_status_64679470" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64679470" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64679470" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a rel="nofollow" id="comment_link_64679470" name="comment_link_64679470" href="//yro.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23409794&amp;cid=64679470" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64679470)" >A machine that can find bugs ...</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64679470" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64679470); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~davide+marney">davide marney</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~davide+marney">( 231845 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64679470"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64679470"><p>Is a machine that can insert exploits and back doors just as easily as it could implement a fix. Even better, it could insert evil code disguised as a fix or cooperating with a fix. This has obvious military and intelligence applications. I'm not saying I'm opposed, necessarily, though that is my default position, I'm just saying that DARPA spends money for the benefit of the US government, not out of the goodness of their open-sourced hearts.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64679470">

</div>
